\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
Factor analysis is a very popular method in statistics that reduces linear
 dimensionality of a particular model.
 The best way to understand factor analysis is to consider a generative
 model.
 A basic factor analysis model is of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
x & = & Lf+\epsilon,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the observed random vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathbf{R}^{r}$
\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $r\leq n$
\end_inset

) is a random vector of common factor variables or scores, 
\begin_inset Formula $L\in\mathbf{R}^{n\times r}$
\end_inset

 is a matrix of factor loadings, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\in\mathbf{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of uncorrelated random variables.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The observed random vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 may contain series of achievement tests, psychological evaluation, intellectual
 performance etc.
 Without loss of generality, we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is mean-centered 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}(x)=0$
\end_inset

, the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 are uncorrelated, and the covariance matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the identity matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{cov}(\epsilon)=D=\mathbf{diag}(d_{1},d_{2},\ldots,d_{n}).$
\end_inset

 Then the covariance matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 can be written as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma=X+D,
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $X=LL^{T}$
\end_inset

 is the covariance matrix corresponding to the common factors.
 The statistical method of factor analysis involves looking at 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 samples generated by the model (1), 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default
, given 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\ldots,x_{N}$
\end_inset

 generated by (1) we want to estimate the matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Optimization problem in consideration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimization problem to determine the matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $X,D$
\end_inset

 can be written as: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ll}
\textup{minimize} & \left\Vert \Sigma-X-D\right\Vert _{F}^{2}\\
\textup{subject to} & D=\mathbf{diag}(d)\\
 & d\geq0\\
 & X\succeq0\\
 & \mathbf{rank}(X)\leq r\\
 & \Sigma-D\succeq0\\
 & \|X\|_{2}\leq M,
\end{array}\tag{FACTOR-ANALYSIS}\label{eq:factor_analysis}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\mathbf{S}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and the diagonal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $D\in\mathbf{S}^{n}$
\end_inset

 with nonnegative diagonal entries are the decision variables, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma\in\mathbf{S}_{+}^{n}$
\end_inset

 (a positive semidefinite matrix), 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\mathbf{Z}_{+},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in\mathbf{R}_{++}$
\end_inset

 are the problem data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A proper solution for the optimization problem above requires that both
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 are positive semidefinite.
 Furthermore, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma-D$
\end_inset

, which is the covariance matrix for the common parts of the variables,
 is not positive semidefinite, that would as embarrassing as having a negative
 unique variance in 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, as noted by ten Berge here (page 326).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Nuclear norm heuristic.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimization problem above is nonconvex.
 To approximately solve it, we use the nuclear norm heuristic.
 In this heuristic, we solve the following relaxed convex optimization problem:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\textup{minimize} & \left\Vert \Sigma-X-D\right\Vert _{F}^{2}+\lambda\left\Vert X\right\Vert _{*}\\
\textup{subject to} & D=\mathbf{diag}(d)\\
 & d\geq0\\
 & X\succeq0\\
 & \Sigma-D\succeq0\\
 & \|X\|_{2}\leq M,
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a positive parameter that is related to the rank of the decision variable
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Note that, as 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is positive semidefinite, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\|X\|_{*}=\mathbf{tr}(X),$
\end_inset

for this reason this heuristic is also called minimum trace factor analysis
 as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To compute the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 corresponding to a desired 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{rank}(X)\leq r$
\end_inset

 we solve the relaxed problem for different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, and find the smallest value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 for which we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{rank}(X)\leq r$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\end_body
